<HR size="1" color="#003366">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Here's one Baels:<P>Enchanters (along with clerics) get the lull line of spells.  These spells are single target and supposedly cha based as far as resists go.  Now, druids/rangers get Harmony which is AoE based.  The lull spells are resisted most of the time in my experience (with 195 cha).  The Harmony spell is never resisted.  I've talked with many enchanters about the lull series and I know ZERO enchanters that even attempt it at high lvl because it's basically a deathwish.  Since the Harmony spell is far more powerful than the single target lull series, why is lull so succeptible to failure?  I would expect the AoE spell to be resisted more, and the lull (since it's single target) to be very reliable.  Frankly I couldn't care less that Harmony isn't resistable, but Verant could at least make the lull series more like y to not attract attention in the case of a failure thus making the lull spells actually usable.  Lull line spells are suppose to be camp busters, but they suck so hard that nobody ever uses them.  They should either fix them or give us something that's useful.
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#003366">
